## 3. UI/UX Polish: Map Enhancements & Theming
### A. The CSS Invert Dark Mode Map Hack
* Bypassed rate-limited providers by using standard, highly-detailed OpenStreetMap base tiles (`https://tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png`).
* Implemented a zero-latency Dark Mode via CSS hardware filtering: `.dark-tiles .leaflet-tile-pane { filter: invert(100%) hue-rotate(180deg) brightness(95%) contrast(90%); }`. 
* Selectively excluded map markers, polylines, popups, and UI overlays from inversion using `.leaflet-marker-pane`, `.leaflet-popup-pane { filter: none; }` rules.

### B. Focus Mode Dimming Effect
* When a route is actively displayed, added a `route-active` conditional class to the Map container.
* CSS applies `.route-active .leaflet-tile-pane { opacity: 0.55; transition: opacity 0.6s ease; }`, significantly dimming the map background grid, while keeping the bright `#00D4AA` teal route polyline at 100% opacity for maximum contrast and emphasis.

### C. Premium Highway Labels
* Replaced standard leaflet popups with custom `L.divIcon` HTML overlays.
* Using `.road-label-icon { width: auto !important; border: none !important; }` to override Leaflet container defaults and prevent 0x0 clipping issues.
* Using `.road-label` with Google Maps-style padding, `border-radius: 5px`, dropping a subtle `box-shadow`, and using the `IBM Plex Mono` font to emulate authentic highway shields floating cleanly along the travel route.

